{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:49:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:49:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17464"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17464"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.11,0.11,0.68,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10154"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70833"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10154"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56300"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5388"},{"type":"tags","id":"5463"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"},{"type":"tags","id":"12703"},{"type":"tags","id":"12704"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23754"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32601"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70833"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner requesting screening for breast cancer. The doctor explains the importance of understanding how reliable different screening tests are at detecting disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes sensitivity in diagnostic testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Proportion of people with disease among all positive tests","Proportion of true negatives among all people without disease","Proportion of correct results among all test results","Proportion of true positives among all people with disease","Proportion of people without disease among all negative tests"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of true positives among all people with disease\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct definition of sensitivity. It measures how well a test can identify those who truly have the condition. A sensitivity of 90% means the test correctly identifies 90% of people who have the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other diagnostic test measures:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of people with disease among all positive tests\u003C/strong\u003E represents positive predictive value, which measures the likelihood that a positive test result truly indicates disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of true negatives among all people without disease\u003C/strong\u003E represents specificity, which measures how well a test identifies those who do not have the condition.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of correct results among all test results\u003C/strong\u003E represents accuracy, which measures the overall correctness of test results including both positive and negative outcomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eproportion of people without disease among all negative tests\u003C/strong\u003E represents negative predictive value, which measures the likelihood that a negative test result truly indicates absence of disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA highly sensitive test is particularly useful for ruling out disease when negative (SnOUT rule) because it has few false negatives. The mathematical formula for sensitivity is: true positives / (true positives + false negatives).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sensitivity measures the proportion of true positive cases correctly identified by a test.","A highly sensitive test is most useful for ruling out disease when negative (SnOUT).","Sensitivity is calculated as: true positives / (true positives + false negatives)."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021.","Peacock, Janet L., and Phil J. Peacock, Oxford Handbook of Medical Statistics 2e, 2 edn, Oxford Medical Handbooks (Oxford, 2020; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Mar. 2020), https://doi.org/10.1093/med/9780198743583.001.0001"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56300"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17464"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56300"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T14:25:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T14:26:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10154"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70833"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"